Hi @darconeous,

Thanks for kicking off this discussion.  Top-level, there seems to be two ways to go here:

1) A dedicated otPlatSpiSlave API as you propose.  Split the inheritance tree of NcpBase as follows:

```
       NcpBase
              |
       NcpProtocolSpinel  (currently collapsed into NcpBase)
       /             \
 NcpUart    NcpSpiSlave
```

2) Keep the existing otPlatSerial API, and have the platform figure out how to handle packetization.  Keep the current NcpBase inheritence tree:
```
       NcpBase
              |
       NcpProtocolSpinel  (currently collapsed into NcpBase)
              |
       Ncp (uses generic otPlatSerial for either SPI or UART as decided by platform)
```

I had always assumed we'd go down path (2), but either are valid.  The way I had thought otPlatSerial could work with a SPI Slave implementation is as follows:

```
ThreadError otPlatSerialEnable(void) 
{
    // Enable SPI Slave bus driver, and gpios: 
    // chip select (CS), slave-to-host signal irq (TO_HOST), host-to-slave signal (FROM_HOST).
}

ThreadError otPlatSerialDisable(void) 
{
    // Opposite of Enable, as appropriate for platform.
}

ThreadError otPlatSerialSend(const uint8_t *aBuf, uint16_t aBufLength) 
{
    // Copy outbound packet to internal driver tx_buffer, signal TO_HOST gpio, and wait for master to pull data
}

void platformSpiSlaveIsr(void)
{
    // SPI transaction / CS IRQ: handle master transaction.  CS assumed to surround a complete packet.
    // Read any data from master into an internal rx_buffer.  Write data from tx_buffer out.
}

extern void otPlatSerialSendDone(void) 
{
    // Send at end of SPI transaction whenever tx_buffer is successfully sent out.
}

extern void otPlatSerialReceived(const uint8_t *aBuf, uint16_t aBufLength)
{
    // Sent up to application from task context when rx_buffer is filled.  rx_buffer may be cleared by driver when this returns.
}
```

The main question with method (2) is how is the length of tx_buffer communicated from slave to master?  A simple way to do that would be to define a short SPI header that prepends each transaction payload that would minimally send the length of the packet.  

For basic flow control, one could assume GPIOs provide direction for a half-duplex utilization of the bus  where a master essentially performs padded "read" transactions anytime TO_HOST is signaled (setting FROM_HOST to low), and performs pure "write" transactions when FROM_HOST is asserted.

Host-to-Slave
```
FROM_HOST = 1
SPI     CS:    1 0 --------------------------------- 1
SPI  HOST:     [len][data ---- ]
SPI SLAVE:    [0][0 ----- 0]
```

Slave-to-Host
```
TO_HOST = (pulse 1 to signal to master to pull data)
FROM_HOST = 0
SPI     CS:    1 0 --------------------------------- 1
SPI SLAVE:     [len][data ---- ]
SPI  HOST:    [0][0 ----- 0]
```

@bjwatson Could you comment on the plans here?

This past sequence of commits changes the public surface of GAX, so we will need to update the code generator templates and release new versions of the GAPIC libraries for `google-cloud-python` to be able to pick these changes up. It will be more efficient to bundle the regeneration together with a few other breaking changes to GAX/GAPIC that are en route, but that might also mean more time -- probably closer to EOQ.

If it's needed sooner, we can do the regeneration for the auth changes separately.

Oh, also, on the topic of `default_strides`: I noticed that the current implementation
```C++
std::fill(strides.begin(), strides.end(), itemsize);
for (size_t i = 0; i < ndim - 1; i++)
    for (size_t j = 0; j < ndim - 1 - i; j++)
        strides[j] *= shape[ndim - 1 - i];
```
could be simplified to the more efficient
```C++
strides[ndim - 1] = itemsize;
for (size_t i = 1; i < ndim; ++i)
    strides[ndim - 1 - i] = strides[ndim - i] * shape[ndim - i];
```

